The Vulnerability of a Flat World
The world is flat!
Says columnist Thomas Friedman. Friedman chose this highly provocative title for his bestseller in order to make people aware of the astonishing impact technology has on the world economy.
Distances are shrinking.
Geographic barriers can no longer easily provide protection.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States are all forced to face the challenges of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak to are likely to be far away in India.
Skeptics have pointed out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As one person said, the world is not flat, but rather "undulating".
The contour map of global economic activity shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Not only that, distance has by no means lost its significance.
Even neighboring countries with lower tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, have much more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Although Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, Vancouver's trade with the much farther away Toronto is far greater than its trade with the nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman still put forward an important point.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence between different continents, a history as long as human history, witnessing the migration of races and religions, as well as trade along the ancient Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it is developing faster and more deeply.
After the first transatlantic submarine cable was laid in 1868, Europe and the United States could communicate within just a minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes depicted a British person living in London ordering goods from all over the world by telephone and then sitting at home waiting to receive them in the afternoon.
But Keynes' British people were a special exception of the wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy goods from all over the world at their local supermarkets.
Similarly, instant global communication emerged 20 years ago, but it was economically beyond the reach of the majority of people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an Internet café and gain capabilities that were once possessed only by governments, multinational corporations, and a few individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant decline in the costs of computing, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly accessible.
Just 10 years ago, two-thirds of Internet users were concentrated in the United States.
Today, Internet users in the United States account for less than a quarter of the global user base.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have access to information has reached a record high in human history.
Non-state actors now possess capabilities that were once held only by governments.
The position of the nation-state as a principal actor in world politics will not change in the near future, but it must learn to share this huge stage with more participants, including organizations like Oxfam, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like Al-Qaeda.
But this process of flattening is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred before.
The world economy was highly integrated in 1914, but during the following 30 years, economic interdependence among countries continuously declined.
It was not until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had previously achieved, although it was still heavily divided by the Iron Curtain.
World War I was the catalyst for this reversal, and during both world wars and the global Cold War, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflected deeper issues caused by economic development in the 19th century, such as domestic inequality.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, and the result was abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism—reaching their peak, which led to the fragmentation of nations and the world.
The welfare state system in the West after World War II provided a safety net for people who were affected by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the benefits brought about by international economic interdependence.
Some analysts argue that today's role of China is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequality, constantly moving towards nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, and ultimately triggering world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, the economies of Britain and Germany were also highly interdependent before 1914.
However, this line of reasoning is not fully sound.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of Britain.
However, even if China maintains its current high growth rate, its economy is unlikely to catch up with that of the United States within at least 20 years.
What poses a greater threat to the flat world are the non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in an unannounced attack than the Japanese government did in its Pearl Harbor attack in 1941.
I refer to this phenomenon as the privatization of war.
If such forces were to gain control of nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo dramatic changes.
At that time, the movement of people and goods across borders would become even more difficult.
If these forces disrupted the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which holds two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic downturn similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen the forces of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major drivers of globalization.
So far, policy has further reinforced the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken a leading role in promoting policies that remove barriers.
But the events described above could reverse such policies.
Some critics of globalization may be willing to see such an outcome.
But such an outcome, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst situations in two areas—namely, the reversal of the trend of economic globalization that spreads technology and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization are further consolidated, such as war, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If that is indeed the case, the flat world would become a desert.
